It seems to me that this is a little bit over-complicated especially because of the unnecessary reliance on the never-preferred arg-captor which led to loop assertion:) On top that the any() matcher does not make the implementation safe to changes. I'd suggest you rewrite this in a more simplified manner. Few tips:
- avoid arg capture, prefer ArgumentMatcher if no equals/hashcode contracts exists (or implement it). Arg captor does quite fit the BDD style of testing, where readability is crucial and you want to read the test step-by-step (from definition, through execution to assertion). Asserting values that are part of execution seems to break this e2e flow. 
- avoid any matchers - using them usually is a shortcut that makes the test easily breakable
- when dealing with big pojos that are json representations consider using test resources for providing the json file (and ser/deser it)instead of constructing bloated object structures for test data inside the test class. Always have readability in mind.

Here is a quick example of I'd recommend rewriting the tests:

    @Test
    public void shouldDelegateNewInstanceCreation() throws Exception {
        RequestDetails expectedRequestDetails = new RequestDetails();
        expectedRequestDetails.setAdditionalProperty("name", "value");
        String payload = objectMapper.writeValueAsString(expectedRequestDetails);
        MsoResponseWrapper expectedResponse = new MsoResponseWrapper(200, "test123");
        given(msoBusinessLogic.createSvcInstance(expectedRequestDetails)).willReturn(expectedResponse);

        mockMvc.perform(post("/mso/mso_create_svc_instance")
            .content(payload)
            .contentType(APPLICATION_JSON))
            .andExpect(status().isOk())
            .andExpect(content().json(objectMapper.writeValueAsString(expectedResponse)));
        verify(cloudService).enrichRequestWithCloudOwner(expectedRequestDetails);
    }
